Case started at 1225h. At 1236h, baseline O2 on HFNO with CO2 monitoring started @30L/min. At 1258h, flow rate increased to 50L/min. At 14:05h, patient was restless and uncomfortable; AA decreased flow rate to 40L/min. At 1518h, AA and staff anesthesiologist couldn't get a CO2 tracing; switched HFNO to face mask @10L/min. Regarding AA's rating about the level of difficulty using HFNO, it was difficult to monitor capnography with the sensor, not to use the oxygen delivery device itself.    Post-procedure, patient was groggy in the recovery bay and unable to provide response to satisfaction questionnaire. The next morning, visited patient on the short stay unit where patient was alert and sitting in a chair but was unable to communicate in English without family member present. At 1430h, visited the patient to complete the survey with family member present to translate but patient became progressively agitated with the questions. Unable to fully complete the survey.

This pt. was randomized to receive HFNO. Due to non-comitant care, the AAs prefer applying the face mask over the HFNO to monitor capnography. The pt. stated the face mask over the HFNO was 'too uncomfortable' and requested to receive oxygen through just the face mask. This pt. did not receive HFNO for the procedure.
When the case ended, and the HFNO was removed, the pt. c/o needing 'more air' and was SOB. AA determined O2 sats 100% on RA. Verbally coached pt.through breaths and symptoms resolved.
Some indentations left on skin from face mask.

No adverse effects noted.     AA commented that they were unable to achieve end-tidal CO2 monitoring with HFNO. RA trouble- shooted and was able to achieve capnography monitoring with consistent waveforms by mid-procedure.

AA informed RA that patient would be receiving conscious sedation. Fellow opted to use only local anaesthetic for the procedure instead of conscious sedation. Patient did not receive any sedation from AA.     No adverse events.

Patient felt uncomfortable because the ETCO2 sensor had to be repositioned throughout the procedure.     AA had difficulty monitoring end-tidal CO2 with HFNO. RA assisted in troubleshooting to receive a reading. Nearing the end of the case, there was a line blockage despite changing the ETCO2 tubing, potentially due to condensation built up in the water trap. AA tech was contacted to replace the water trap during the case and reading was re-established. AA commented on the difficulty of using the ETCO2 sensor and that we were lucky in this case that the patient didn't require further sedation. AA said that they would not use HFNO with ETCO2 next time if there was a similar case.

1 min after applying the HFNO, the patient complained of the HFNO being 'very uncomfortable', and stated 'I feel like I'm suffocating'. RA titrated oxygen flow down from 30L/min to 15L/min. Patient did not tolerate it well, stating, 'it makes me feel like I need to breathe through my mouth. I still feel like I can't breathe very well. My chest hurts'. RA instructed patient to try breathing through her nose as much as possible. After a few minutes, the patient was still uncomfortable. AA and RA decided to switch HFNO for facemask. Patient reported feeling more comfortable with the facemask.

Patient reported that the facemask was 'very uncomfortable', and that 'the mask was too small for my face. It kept sliding on and off. When it fell off my nose they moved it up, but then it would slide up and into my eyes'.
